<hl>
<seg id=1> Most of the Hong Kong people don't want to be called Chinese. </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> French News Agency, Hong Kong According to an announcement of a public opinion poll yesterday, although Hong Kong Had returned to China, most of Hong Kong people didn't want to themselves Chinese. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> According to the public opinion poll, among the 6,500,000 Hong Kong citizens, 40% of them wanted to call themselves "Hong-Kongese". 22.3% of them wanted to call themselves "the Hong Kong Chinese", and 20.6% "the Chinese living in Hong Kong". </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> It's the Social Science Research Center of Hong Kong University that carried out the public opinion poll. </seg>
<seg id=5> Among the 517 people who were interviewed, only 20.6% wanted to call themselves Chinese, and 1.6% of them didn't give a clear answer or had no answer. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> Such an investigation was done after half a year since Hong Kong had returned to China, and 35.9% of the people called themselves "Hong-Kongese", while 18% of them called themselves Chinese. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> Hong Kong has returned to China for 15 months, and the Hong Kong government has been trying to remind the citizens that they are Chinese. </seg>
<seg id=8> The Hong Kong officials complained that after about 150 years under British colonialist rule, many Hong Kong citizens felt difficult in the recognition of their status. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> Dong Jianhua, the Leader of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Zone, said the day before yesterday in his National Day message: "It's my pleasure to be a Chinese, and I am very proud of the development of our country." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=10> In order to raise the sense of Chinese citizenship in Hong Kong citizens, the Citizens' Education Improvement Association in Hong Kong wrote and published a book full of pictures named "I am Chinese". </seg>
</p>
